941
01:03:19,000 --> 01:03:21,000
You don't mean a Puerto Rican.

942
01:03:21,000 --> 01:03:27,000
You only mean a person in America who is black.

943
01:03:27,000 --> 01:03:29,000
So it should be capitalized.

944
01:03:29,000 --> 01:03:38,000
And I feel that it's in and insult when you see in the papers different groups of people and then a lower case letter of a black.

945
01:03:38,000 --> 01:03:39,000
You know.

946
01:03:40,000 --> 01:03:41,000
Yeah.

947
01:03:41,000 --> 01:03:43,000
I wrote a letter.

948
01:03:43,000 --> 01:03:50,000
Oh, also in that package, I have a letter that I wrote to this local paper and I'm surprised they printed it.

949
01:03:50,000 --> 01:04:00,000
They talked about two black women doing something fraudulent and it should you see them call the police.

950
01:04:00,000 --> 01:04:03,000
So I wrote them a long letter.

951
01:04:03,000 --> 01:04:06,000
I said, you named two black women.

952
01:04:06,000 --> 01:04:11,000
You have made it dangerous for me to walk downtown.

953
01:04:11,000 --> 01:04:12,000
No description.

954
01:04:12,000 --> 01:04:13,000
That's it.

955
01:04:13,000 --> 01:04:14,000
That was the only description.

956
01:04:14,000 --> 01:04:16,000
Yeah, it's in that packet.

957
01:04:16,000 --> 01:04:17,000
Yeah.

958
01:04:17,000 --> 01:04:18,000
Yeah.

959
01:04:18,000 --> 01:04:25,000
Have you written any other letters to the editor over the years or other issues that got under your schedule?

960
01:04:25,000 --> 01:04:31,000
Only about the black issue have I written to the very, I wrote it to the LA Times and I'm always writing letters.

961
01:04:31,000 --> 01:04:37,000
Well, but I write good letters to compliment people when they should be.

962
01:04:37,000 --> 01:04:47,000
I felt I was writing my bicycle and I turned the corner too fast and for the first time I didn't have my helmet on and I hit my head on the fire hydrant around the corner.

963
01:04:47,000 --> 01:04:51,000
And I'm down there crying like an ugly ugly thing just crying.

964
01:04:51,000 --> 01:04:54,000
And I look uglier than ugly when I cry.

965
01:04:54,000 --> 01:04:57,000
And two men got out of their truck and they said, are you okay?

966
01:04:57,000 --> 01:05:00,000
I said, oh no, I'm crying.

967
01:05:00,000 --> 01:05:02,000
Why man held my hand as well?

968
01:05:02,000 --> 01:05:04,000
Then I thought, oh god, you're looking uglier.

969
01:05:04,000 --> 01:05:05,000
Stop crying.

970
01:05:05,000 --> 01:05:07,000
So I stopped crying.

971
01:05:07,000 --> 01:05:14,000
But you know, there were two white men helping a black lady or two men helping a female for that matter.

972
01:05:14,000 --> 01:05:15,000
Yeah.

973
01:05:15,000 --> 01:05:17,000
So I haven't felt anything.

974
01:05:17,000 --> 01:05:20,000
Oh, I mean, I'm sure they're.

975
01:05:20,000 --> 01:05:26,000
As I said, if I feel anything, I move on.

976
01:05:26,000 --> 01:05:31,000
I might be wrapping up here.

977
01:05:31,000 --> 01:05:34,000
Do you think about that?

978
01:05:34,000 --> 01:05:40,000
You know, what you did at Virginia Union University and being part of this protest.

979
01:05:40,000 --> 01:05:43,000
As something very historic, you did it being a participant.

980
01:05:43,000 --> 01:05:44,000
I do now.

981
01:05:44,000 --> 01:05:45,000
I didn't think it was.

982
01:05:45,000 --> 01:05:47,000
I thought it was something we were doing.

983
01:05:47,000 --> 01:05:51,000
You know, it was one of many people across the country.

984
01:05:51,000 --> 01:05:54,000
But I didn't realize it until afterwards.

985
01:05:54,000 --> 01:05:57,000
In fact, I didn't realize it until I was at a school.

986
01:05:57,000 --> 01:05:59,000
And I was in the library.

987
01:05:59,000 --> 01:06:04,000
And the lady says, Dr. Grinnell, do you know anything about the Civil Rights Movement?

988
01:06:04,000 --> 01:06:06,000
And I said, yeah, I do.

989
01:06:06,000 --> 01:06:08,000
I said, I was in it.

990
01:06:08,000 --> 01:06:09,000
She says, you were?

991
01:06:09,000 --> 01:06:11,000
Oh, no, not a big deal.

992
01:06:11,000 --> 01:06:14,000
You know, then I realized she's young.

993
01:06:14,000 --> 01:06:16,000
She's a young teacher.

994
01:06:17,000 --> 01:06:19,000
And that's when it hit me.

995
01:06:19,000 --> 01:06:21,000
I guess it was a big deal.

996
01:06:21,000 --> 01:06:22,000
Yeah.

997
01:06:23,000 --> 01:06:26,000
That's a great finish in one, I think.

998
01:06:26,000 --> 01:06:27,000
Oh, thank you.

999
01:06:27,000 --> 01:06:29,000
Well, it wasn't a deal.

1000
01:06:29,000 --> 01:06:30,000
Yeah, yeah.

1001
01:06:30,000 --> 01:06:34,000
Well, let me just ask you, was there anything that I didn't ask that you thought I might ask or that I should have asked?

1002
01:06:34,000 --> 01:06:38,000
No, I'll think of it later on, but it probably won't be important anyway.

1003
01:06:38,000 --> 01:06:40,000
So, no.

1004
01:06:40,000 --> 01:06:41,000
Well, thank you so much.

1005
01:06:41,000 --> 01:06:42,000
But thank you.

1006
01:06:42,000 --> 01:06:43,000
I appreciate it.

1007
01:06:43,000 --> 01:06:46,000
And I'll tell you what you have to do while you're here since I made a cake for you guys.

1008
01:06:46,000 --> 01:06:47,000
You have to eat it.

1009
01:06:47,000 --> 01:06:48,000
I made a pound cake.

1010
01:06:48,000 --> 01:06:50,000
Well, whether you like it or not.

1011
01:06:50,000 --> 01:06:51,000
You have to take off.

1012
01:06:51,000 --> 01:06:52,000
Okay.

1013
01:06:52,000 --> 01:06:55,000
You've done your sacrifice.

1014
01:06:55,000 --> 01:07:04,000
This has been a presentation of the Library of Congress and the Smithsonian National Museum of African American History and Culture.
